{"id":707,"date":"2022-01-09T10:10:00","date_gmt":"2022-01-09T10:10:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=707"},"modified":"2022-01-08T20:31:18","modified_gmt":"2022-01-08T20:31:18","slug":"archive-compress-unpack-and-uncompress-files-using-tar-star-gzip-and-bzip2","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=707","title":{"rendered":"Archive, compress, unpack, and uncompress files using tar, star, gzip, and bzip2"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h3>What are archives files? <\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>The files archived in a gzip file are usually, but not always, compressed. This saves space and also makes it easier to send them as email attachments. Zip files are also convenient for grouping data files. Rather than transporting, copying, or sending a number of files; you can gzip them and easily work with one gzip file.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Gzip files (and other archives) contain information in a highly encoded form. In this form, the information is not directly usable by other applications. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>What is tar?<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>tar does not do compression, it just creates archives. It relies on a 3rd party, like gzip for compression.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>gzip FILE compresses FILE and renames it FILE.gz<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">gzip &lt;text_file_name&gt;<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"112\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?resize=640%2C112&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-708\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?w=697&amp;ssl=1 697w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?resize=300%2C53&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?resize=24%2C4&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?resize=36%2C6&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-61.png?resize=48%2C8&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>gunzip FILE.gz decompresses FILE and renames it FILE<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">gunzip &lt;gziped_file_name&gt;<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"111\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?resize=640%2C111&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-709\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?w=703&amp;ssl=1 703w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?resize=300%2C52&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?resize=24%2C4&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?resize=36%2C6&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-62.png?resize=48%2C8&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>You cannot compress a DIRECTORY with gzip, so you need to create an archive, which is just a grouping of all the files in a directory, basically.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>tar -cvf FILE.tar creates an archive called FILE (not compressed)<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">tar -cvf &lt;new_directory_name.tar&gt; &lt;directory_name_we_want_to_tar&gt;<\/pre>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"244\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?resize=640%2C244&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-710\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?w=662&amp;ssl=1 662w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?resize=300%2C114&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?resize=24%2C9&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?resize=36%2C14&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-63.png?resize=48%2C18&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>tar -cvzf FILE.tar.gz creates a compressed archive using gzip (-z flag)<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"> tar -cvf &lt;new_directory_name.tar.gz&gt; &lt;directory_name_we_want_to_tar_and_compress&gt; <\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>By default, when you extract a compressed archive with <strong>tar -xvf FILE.tar.gz<\/strong>, it will overwrite any file with the same name. To avoid issues you can use a flag (-d): <strong>tar -dvf FILE.tar.gz<\/strong> which will display the DIFF (d for DIFF) between what&#8217;s in the archive and what&#8217;s on the current system.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>What is star?<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Star (which is not installed on RHEL by default) can be used for large data sets. And it doesn&#8217;t overwrite files that are newer than the files in the archive. It gives you more security.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To install&nbsp;<code>star<\/code>, run the&nbsp;<code>yum install star<\/code>&nbsp;command as the Linux root user.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There is a good exercise on the official Red Hat site which shows you the advantages of the stat. You can check it out <a href=\"https:\/\/access.redhat.com\/documentation\/en-us\/red_hat_enterprise_linux\/6\/html\/security-enhanced_linux\/sect-security-enhanced_linux-maintaining_selinux_labels_-archiving_files_with_star\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Simple syntax for compressing\/decompressing<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">star -xattr -H=exustar -c -f=test.star file{1,2,3}<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">star -x -f=test.star<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>What is bzip?<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Gzip and bzip2 are functionally equivalent. There once was a bzip, but it seems to have completely vanished off the IT worls\/ Other common compression formats are zip, rar and 7z; these three do both compression and archiving (packing multiple files into one). <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here are some typical ratings in terms of speed, availability and typical compression ratio<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>decompression speed (fast &gt; slow): gzip, zip &gt; 7z &gt; rar &gt; bzip2\ncompression speed (fast &gt; slow): gzip, zip &gt; bzip2 &gt; 7z &gt; rar\ncompression ratio (better &gt; worse): 7z &gt; rar, bzip2 &gt; gzip &gt; zip\navailability (unix): gzip &gt; bzip2 &gt; zip &gt; 7z &gt; rar\navailability (windows): zip &gt; rar &gt; 7z &gt; gzip, bzip2<\/code><\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The syntax <\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">bzip2 -z textfile.txt<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>-z :&nbsp;<\/strong>This option forces compression. It is an opposite command of decompression<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>d :&nbsp;<\/strong>This option is used for decompression of compressed files.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">bzip2 -d textfile.txt.bz2<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>What are archives files? The files archived in a gzip file are usually, but not [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":751,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"nf_dc_page":"","om_disable_all_campaigns":false,"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[219],"tags":[251,257,252,220,258,255,254,253],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/rhsa-understand-and-use-essential-tools-2.png?fit=1280%2C720&ssl=1","_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/707"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fcomments&post=707"}],"version-history":[{"count":2,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/707\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":725,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/707\/revisions\/725"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/media\/751"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fmedia&parent=707"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fcategories&post=707"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Ftags&post=707"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}